  "detailedRequirements": "<p><em>This challenge is part of Project SERENITY: a refresh of the topcoder challenge lifecycle. There are many challenges before it and will be many after it but you should be able to clone this repo: https://github.com/topcoderinc/serenity-core, grok the README and be up to speed in a few minutes. &nbsp;</em></p>\n\n<p>We have a nice functioning challenge listing table using ngGrid and now we also have a well designed challenge listing table prototype that has the final style and functionality we are looking for. &nbsp; The goal of this challenge is to make our challenge listing table from: https://github.com/topcoderinc/serenity-core (packages/challenges/public/views/list.html) to look like https://github.com/topcoderinc/lc1-serenity-challenge-prototype &nbsp;or you can see the live demo here: http://lc-proto.herokuapp.com/#/challenges. &nbsp; We suspect that we &nbsp;can stylize ngGrid to look exactly like the prototype however we are looking for any feedback of why we can or can&rsquo;t do this. &nbsp; &nbsp;Especially for the pagination we are concerned if this is more than just a style/ config options exercise and we need to modify the directive. &nbsp; For example we would like the to hard code the page size to 25 and hide the pageSize drop-down.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>1. &nbsp;Modify the current ngGrid challenge listing table from the serenity-core repo to look like the prototype (http://lc-proto.herokuapp.com/#/challenges. &nbsp;as much as possible.<br />\n2. &nbsp;You may ignore the filter icon at the time since it is not included in the prototype.&nbsp;<br />\n3. &nbsp;Pay particular attention to the pagination in the grid footer and replicate the footer to be like the prototype<br />\n4. &nbsp;Please don&rsquo;t use the icons from the prototype. use fa-edit and fa-trash<br />\n5. &nbsp;Note that the prototype always shows the sort icons even when not in use (shaded) and highlights them when they are active.<br />\n6. &nbsp;The timezone on the prototype is assumed to be EST however it looks like the date format filter does not take a time zone as a parameter. &nbsp;If you can find an elegant way to adjust this fine otherwise we can just keep the UTC time and address that later.<br />\n7. &nbsp;An Ideal solution will hide or disable the back/next if the count is less then 25</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n",
